Foxp2+/+ mice subjected to 0.1 mg/kg intraperitoneal injection of PTX show decreased rotarod performance and learning rates, whereas these were increased in Foxp2S321X/+ mice (latency to fall: days 1–5: Foxp2+/+ 71.7 ± 12.4, 91.7 ± 5.5, 96.4 ± 4.7, 104.4 ± 1.2, 114 ± 3.2. Foxp2S321X/+ 33.8 ± 4.5, 59.8 ± 5.7, 77.4 ± 5.3, 91.8 ± 1.1, 103.2 ± 3.61. NS learning rate: Foxp2+/+ 7.2 ± 2.5, 5 ± 2.3, 3.4 ± 1.9, − 0.1 ± 4.0, 3.6 ± 3.8. Foxp2S321X/+, 0.76 ± 1.2, 5.9 ± 2.5, 6.4 ± 1.9, 0.0 ± 1.8, 4.3 ± 3.9. NS, repeated measures ANOVA). e Average RPM at which mice fail the accelerating rotarod task during session 4 and 5 in vehicle and PTX conditions (vehicle, Foxp2+/+ 24.1 ± 0.94 RPM, Foxp2S321X/+ 12 ± 0.96 RPM, P < 0.001. PTX, Foxp2+/+ 16.7 ± 0.4 RPM, Foxp2S321X+ 15.3 ± 0.372 RPM, NS, two-sided Students’ T test). For all treatment conditions, N = 5 mice. ***P < 0.001

